"""
MKT Context Commentary — Exodus 13–15
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-exodus-13-15.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/exodus.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/exodus.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/exodus.json (existing entries)

Key decisions in this range:
- Song of the Sea (ch15) treated as archaic Hebrew poetry with ANE divine warrior background
- "Frontlets between your eyes" (13:9,16) discussed as the origin of tefillin practice
- Via Maris (coastal road) identified as the route God deliberately avoided
- Miriam (15:20) noted as the first person titled "prophetess" in Scripture
- Marah/Elim sequence (15:22-27) treated as the first wilderness testing pattern
- Location identifications (Pi-hahiroth, Migdol, Baal-zephon) noted as debated
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EXODUS_CONTEXT = {
    "13": {
        "1": "<p>The consecration of the firstborn follows immediately after the Passover account. In the ANE, the firstborn was the primary heir bearing the family's legal and cultic continuity — the right of inheritance, the priestly function within the household, and the double portion of property. YHWH's claim on Israel's firstborn grounds the entire system in the exodus event: the firstborn were spared at the cost of Egypt's firstborn; therefore they belong to YHWH.</p>",
        "2": "<p><em>Qadesh-lî kol-bĕkôr</em> — 'Consecrate to me every firstborn': the consecration formula is remarkable in its scope — 'every firstborn that opens the womb among the Israelites, whether human or animal.' In ANE law codes, the firstborn of animals was commonly dedicated to deities; Israel's version anchors this in covenant history rather than nature religion. The firstborn dedication becomes one of the foundational institutions distinguishing Israel from surrounding nations, repeated and elaborated throughout Deuteronomy.</p>",
        "3": "<p>Moses commands Israel to <em>zākar</em> (remember) — a loaded covenant term in Hebrew theology. Covenantal memory is not merely intellectual recall but active participation in the founding event. The Passover Seder (from Second Temple times onward) was designed precisely to effect this: each generation is to regard itself as having personally left Egypt (Mishnah Pesachim 10:5). The word 'Abib' designates the month by the state of the barley crop — 'Abib' means 'fresh/green ears'; it was later renamed Nisan after the Babylonian exile.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The month of Abib (March-April by the solar calendar) was the agricultural new year in ancient Israel, when the barley began to ripen. The Passover timing in the full moon of Abib tied the redemption narrative to the natural calendar — spring, new growth, new life. After the Babylonian exile, Israel adopted the Babylonian name 'Nisan' for this month (Neh 2:1; Esth 3:7), but the agricultural calendar associations remained active.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The list of nations — Canaanites, Hittites, Amorites, Hivites, Jebusites — is the standard Deuteronomic five-nation formula (the 'six-nation' list adds the Girgashites; the 'seven-nation' list is in Deut 7:1). These peoples were the actual pre-Israelite inhabitants of Canaan whose material culture is attested in the Bronze Age archaeological record. The Hittites were an imperial power with their capital at Hattusa in Anatolia; the Jebusites held Jerusalem (Jebus) until David's capture of the city (2 Sam 5:6-9). The list functions as a covenant promise: YHWH will deliver the land despite these established nations.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The seven-day Feast of Unleavened Bread and the one-day Passover were distinct celebrations that became fused in practice. The Passover was a single night's meal (14 Nisan) recalling the exodus; the Feast of Unleavened Bread lasted seven days (15-21 Nisan) with the first and last days as sacred assemblies (Lev 23:6-8). By Second Temple times the two had merged into a continuous eight-day festival. The unleavened bread (<em>maṣṣôt</em>) represented the urgency of departure — no time for dough to rise — and the theological principle that the old corrupting leaven was left behind in Egypt.</p>",
        "7": "<p>'No leavened bread shall be seen with you, and no leaven shall be seen with you in all your territory' — the comprehensive search for and removal of leaven before the Passover became an elaborate ritual in later Jewish practice. The night before Passover, Jewish families conducted a candlelight search of the house (<em>bedikat ḥameṣ</em>, the checking of leaven), burning whatever was found the next morning. Jesus later uses the pervasive nature of leaven as a warning metaphor for corruption: 'Beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees' (Matt 16:6), and Paul applies this directly to the Passover type: 'Cleanse out the old leaven that you may be a new lump' (1 Cor 5:7).</p>",
        "8": "<p>The Passover Haggadah (telling) — 'you shall tell your child on that day' — is the foundation for the most significant pedagogical institution in Israelite religion. The Passover was not merely a memorial meal but an enacted narrative: parents were required to explain the meaning to their children using first-person identification ('because of what YHWH did for <em>me</em> when I came out of Egypt'). The later Passover Seder was structured around the child's four questions (Mishnah Pesachim 10:4), elaborating this command into a full evening of narrative, song, and symbolic foods. The Deuteronomic tradition repeats this pedagogical mandate in Deut 6:20-25.</p>",
        "9": "<p>'This observance shall be to you as a sign on your hand and a reminder between your eyes' — this verse and v.16 are two of the four biblical passages (with Deut 6:8 and 11:18) that were interpreted literally in Second Temple Judaism and written on small scrolls inserted into black leather boxes called <em>tĕpillîn</em> (phylacteries) and bound on the left arm and forehead during morning prayer. The practice is attested from at least the second century BCE (found at Qumran). The metaphorical sense is also present: the memory of the exodus is to be as constantly present as something strapped to the body. Jesus criticizes the performative enlarging of phylacteries (Matt 23:5).</p>",
        "10": "<p>'You shall therefore keep this statute at its appointed time from year to year' — the term <em>mô'ēd</em> (appointed time, set feast) is the technical term for all YHWH's sacred assemblies (Lev 23:2: 'appointed feasts of YHWH'). The festivals were not optional commemorations but binding covenant obligations with the force of divine statute (<em>ḥuqqāh</em>). The annual repetition was designed to rebuild communal identity: each generation re-experienced the founding event by participating in the festival. Israel's liturgical calendar was the primary mechanism for transmitting covenant memory across generations.</p>",
        "11": "<p>The phrase 'when YHWH brings you into the land of the Canaanites, as he swore to you and your fathers' ties the firstborn dedication law to the Abrahamic covenant. The ancestors (Abraham, Isaac, Jacob) received the land promise; the Passover generation now stands on the threshold of its fulfillment. The law is framed as prospective — it will be observed <em>when</em> you enter the land, not just now in the wilderness. This forward-looking framing creates a narrative arc: the exodus is not the end but the means; the land is the goal.</p>",
        "12": "<p>'You shall set apart to YHWH all that first opens the womb' — <em>haʿăbart</em> (cause to pass over/set apart) uses the same root as the Passover (pesach). Every firstborn male of livestock belonged to YHWH. The offering of the firstborn of the flock was among the oldest forms of Israelite sacrifice; Leviticus 27 elaborates the commutation values for animals and humans. The theological claim is radical: the most economically valuable animals (the first of the herd) belong to YHWH before they belong to the farmer.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Donkeys occupy a unique position in the firstborn law: they are firstborn males requiring dedication, but as unclean animals they cannot be offered as sacrifices. They must be <em>redeemed</em> with a lamb (substitution) or, if not redeemed, killed by breaking the neck. This redemption-or-death structure is the same applied to firstborn sons (v.15) — it dramatizes the principle that redemption has a cost. Donkeys were the primary draft animals of the ancient Near East, essential for agriculture and trade, making their redemption economically significant. The lamb substitution foreshadows the Passover lamb logic.</p>",
        "14": "<p>'When in the future your child asks you...' — the catechetical question-and-answer format appears three times in the Passover liturgy (Exod 12:26; 13:8, 14). This pattern became the structural backbone of the Passover Seder's Haggadah, explicitly designed for children's questions. The Mishnah codified four types of children and their questions (Pesachim 10:4) — the wise, the wicked, the simple, and those who cannot ask — each receiving a tailored answer. The underlying theology is that covenant identity is transmitted through narrative, not merely through law: children learn <em>who they are</em> by learning what YHWH <em>did</em>.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The narrative here retells the killing of Egypt's firstborn as the justification for Israel's firstborn dedication — YHWH killed Pharaoh's firstborn because Pharaoh refused to let Israel (YHWH's firstborn son, Exod 4:22-23) go free. The language of redemption (<em>pādāh</em> — to ransom, buy back) embedded in the firstborn law encodes a theology: Israel as a whole was ransomed from Egypt; the firstborn dedication is the ongoing reminder of that ransom. The same verb <em>pādāh</em> describes YHWH's eschatological redemption in Isa 35:10 and is applied to Christ's work in 1 Pet 1:18.</p>",
        "16": "<p>The second occurrence of the tefillin/frontlets command (see v.9); the repetition with slight variation signals the importance of the practice. The 'sign on the hand' and 'frontlets between the eyes' bracket the Passover narrative as a whole: both the freedom from slavery (recounted in the first half of ch.13) and the firstborn dedication (second half) are inscribed on the body. The anthropological dimension is intentional: covenant memory is not merely cognitive but somatic, built into daily practice through physical ritual.</p>",
        "17": "<p>The 'Way of the Philistines' (<em>derek eretz pĕlîštîm</em>) was the major coastal military highway running northeast from Egypt through Gaza — the route that would have taken Israel to Canaan in as little as ten days. Archaeological surveys have confirmed a string of Egyptian military fortresses along this road from the eastern delta to southern Canaan, used to control movement and repel the Hyksos. YHWH's stated reason for avoiding it — 'lest the people reconsider when they see war' — shows divine awareness of the people's fragile faith. The detour through the wilderness was providentially designed to form the nation before they faced military challenges.</p>",
        "18": "<p><em>Ḥămûšîm</em> (v.18) is often translated 'armed' or 'in battle formation' — possibly meaning 'in fivefold formation' (from the root for five), the standard march order for ancient armies. This detail subtly undercuts the people's later complaints about facing the Egyptians (14:11-12): they left Egypt as an organized military force, not as a desperate mob. The phrase 'Sea of Reeds' (Heb. <em>yam-sûp</em>) is the Hebrew name consistently translated 'Red Sea' in the LXX and most versions; its exact identification is debated — possibly one of the lakes in the Sinai isthmus or the Gulf of Suez/Aqaba.</p>",
        "19": "<p>Moses's taking of Joseph's bones (Gen 50:25-26) fulfills the patriarchal oath sworn to Joseph in Egypt. Joseph made his brothers swear on his deathbed that when YHWH visited them and brought them up from Egypt, they would carry his bones with them. The fulfillment is delayed by four centuries (the time of Egyptian slavery) but is remembered by Moses. Joseph is eventually buried at Shechem in the plot of land Jacob had purchased (Josh 24:32) — a detail that ties the conclusion of the Joshua narrative to the Genesis patriarchal promise. Joseph's bones carried through the wilderness are a physical sign of the continuity between the patriarchal and Mosaic periods of covenant history.</p>",
        "20": "<p>Succoth ('booths') is likely Tell el-Maskhuta in the eastern Nile delta, about 50 miles east of Ramesses; some identify it with Tell el-Borg. Etham is on the edge of the wilderness, probably in the vicinity of the modern Suez Canal zone. The movement from Succoth to Etham places Israel at the threshold between the cultivated Nile delta and the Sinai wilderness — from the known world into the unknown, from slavery into the formation period. The Feast of Booths (<em>Sukkot</em>) later recalls this wilderness journey explicitly: 'that your generations may know that I made the people of Israel dwell in booths when I brought them out of the land of Egypt' (Lev 23:43).</p>",
        "21": "<p>The pillar of cloud by day and fire by night is the <em>šĕkînāh</em> — the manifest divine presence — in its most tangible wilderness form. In ancient Egypt, divine images were carried before armies to signify divine presence and protection; YHWH's pillar inverts this: the deity himself goes before his people, not a cultic statue. The cloud (protective from the desert sun) and fire (warmth and light in the cold desert night) are practical provisions as well as theophanies. The image is developed throughout the OT: the divine presence as a fire by night and cloud by day becomes the standard description of YHWH's glory-presence (Isa 4:5).</p>",
        "22": "<p>'Neither the pillar of cloud by day nor the pillar of fire by night ever departed from before the people' — the unbroken continuity of the divine presence through the entire exodus journey is the narrator's theological summary. YHWH did not lead them to the wilderness and abandon them; his presence was constant throughout. Nehemiah reflects on this in his great prayer: 'You did not withdraw your pillar of cloud... nor the pillar of fire by night, to light for them the way in which they should go' (Neh 9:19). The pillar is the visible guarantee of YHWH's covenant commitment to the generation he was forming.</p>"
    },
    "14": {
        "1": "<p>The command for Israel to 'turn back' (<em>šûbû</em>) in v.2 deliberately places them in a strategically vulnerable position — their backs to an impassable sea, Pharaoh behind them. What appears as military incompetence is divinely orchestrated entrapment that will create the occasion for YHWH's definitive self-revelation. The geography of the sea-crossing miracle is framed as theology: YHWH arranges the impossible situation precisely so that the only possible explanation is YHWH himself.</p>",
        "2": "<p>Pi-hahiroth, Migdol, and Baal-zephon are all debated in their exact locations. Pi-hahiroth may mean 'mouth of the canals' or 'house of Hahiroth'; Migdol (Hebrew for 'watchtower') is a common Egyptian placename with several candidates in the eastern delta. Baal-zephon is most significant: it names the sanctuary of Baal Zaphon, a Canaanite storm god whose main Egyptian cult site was in the eastern delta near the sea. YHWH deliberately positions Israel at the boundary of this pagan sacred site — the coming miracle at the sea will be a direct confrontation between YHWH and the claims of the Baal cult over the cosmic waters.</p>",
        "3": "<p>'Pharaoh will think the Israelites are wandering in confusion, hemmed in by the wilderness' — YHWH's strategy includes psychological warfare. Pharaoh's intelligence reports Israel's reversal of direction as tactical disorientation. The divine trap works through the normal exercise of military intelligence: Pharaoh follows his best reading of the situation and walks into what YHWH has arranged. The phrase 'the wilderness has shut them in' uses the same root (<em>sāgar</em>) as closing the doors of the ark (Gen 7:16) — an image of sealed, inescapable enclosure.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The hardening of Pharaoh's heart is stated seven times in chs. 7-11 as caused by Pharaoh himself and seven times as caused by YHWH — the theological symmetry is deliberate. The NT engages this directly: Paul cites Exod 9:16 ('for this purpose I raised you up...') and Exod 33:19 ('I will have mercy on whom I have mercy') in Romans 9:15-17 to ground his argument about divine sovereignty in election. The hardening serves YHWH's larger purpose: 'I will gain glory over Pharaoh and all his army, and the Egyptians shall know that I am YHWH.'</p>",
        "5": "<p>'When the king of Egypt was told that the people had fled' — Pharaoh's regret has a political dimension: slave labor was the economic foundation of Egyptian monument-building. The Ipuwer Papyrus (a composition possibly from the late Middle Kingdom or Second Intermediate Period) describes chaos when servants leave their masters — the loss of the slave workforce was not merely an economic blow but a social catastrophe. Pharaoh's change of heart ('What have we done, that we have let Israel go from serving us?') reflects the recognition of this loss.</p>",
        "6": "<p>Pharaoh personally takes command: 'he had his chariot prepared and took his forces with him.' The Egyptian pharaoh was simultaneously the supreme military commander, divine warrior, and living god. His personal participation in pursuit is consistent with the royal ideology of Egyptian military texts, which consistently portray the pharaoh as the primary agent of military victory. By placing Pharaoh personally in the chase, the narrative sets up the ultimate confrontation: the self-proclaimed divine warrior of Egypt against YHWH the divine warrior.</p>",
        "7": "<p>Six hundred select chariots plus all other chariots of Egypt — Egyptian military documents record the scale of chariot deployments. The battle reliefs of Ramesses II at Karnak and Abu Simbel depict hundreds of chariots in formation. Chariots carried a driver, a shield-bearer, and a warrior; the 'officers' (<em>šālîšîm</em>) were literally 'third-men' — the warriors in the third position. Egyptian chariots were among the most advanced military technology of the Bronze Age, capable of rapid flanking maneuvers that infantry could not counter.</p>",
        "8": "<p>'YHWH hardened the heart of Pharaoh king of Egypt, and he pursued the people of Israel while the Israelites were going out <em>bĕyād rāmāh</em>' — 'with a high hand,' the idiom for bold, open defiance. The phrase is borrowed in Num 15:30 for deliberate, defiant sin ('with a high hand'). Here it describes Israel's exodus as an act of sovereign boldness — they are not sneaking out but departing openly, under YHWH's protection, as victors. The contrast with the nighttime departure of Passover (Exod 12:31-42) shows a progression from liberation to declaration.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The Egyptian pursuit force is itemized: 'all Pharaoh's horses and chariots, and his horsemen and his army' — the same phrase that will appear in the victory Song of the Sea (15:4). The literary parallel is intentional: the full catalog of Pharaoh's military power is listed before the crossing so that its total destruction can be celebrated after. The 'Israelites camping by the sea' at Baal-zephon is the geography of maximum vulnerability — Israel is pinned between the sea and the army.</p>",
        "10": "<p>'The Israelites looked up and saw the Egyptians coming after them' — the verb used here (nāśāʾ ʿênayim) is the same idiom as Abraham looking up to see the ram in the thicket (Gen 22:13) — a literary marker for a surprise divine provision. The Israelites were terrified (<em>wayyîrĕʾû mĕʾōd</em>) and cried out to YHWH. Their terror is understandable: no weapons could stop the Egyptian chariot corps. The narrative deliberately establishes maximum human impossibility before the divine act — no natural explanation will remain available after YHWH acts.</p>",
        "11": "<p>'Were there no graves in Egypt that you brought us to die in the wilderness?' — the first major grumbling speech in the wilderness narrative establishes a pattern that recurs throughout Numbers. The complaint is not merely ingratitude but a theological assertion: that death in Egypt would have been preferable to freedom leading to death in the wilderness. Egypt represented the known misery vs. the unknown danger. This complaint is paradigmatic: the NT's 'Hall of Faith' (Heb 11) and Paul's wilderness typology (1 Cor 10) both reflect on the Exodus generation's failure of nerve as a warning for the church.</p>",
        "12": "<p>'Is this not what we said to you in Egypt, “Leave us alone that we may serve the Egyptians”?' — the people's memory is already rewriting the past. The narrative (Exod 5-12) shows the Israelites expressing hope for deliverance; now they claim to have preferred slavery. This pattern of retrospective idealization of Egypt recurs: in Num 11:5 they remember 'the fish we ate in Egypt for free, the cucumbers, the melons, the leeks, the onions, and the garlic.' Under pressure, human memory romanticizes the known suffering over the unknown freedom — a recurring dynamic in the wilderness generation's psychology.</p>",
        "13": "<p>'Stand firm and see the <em>yĕšûʿat YHWH</em> (salvation/deliverance of YHWH)' — Moses's response is one of the OT's great declarations of faith. <em>Yĕšûʿāh</em> is the noun from the same root as <em>yāšaʿ</em> (to save/deliver), the root of the names Joshua (<em>Yĕhôšûaʿ</em>, 'YHWH saves') and Jesus (<em>Yēšûaʿ</em>). Moses calls the people to stand firm — the same idiom used of soldiers taking their military position (<em>hityyaṣṣĕbû</em>). This is not passive waiting but an active posture of trust: watching for YHWH to act rather than acting from panic.</p>",
        "14": "<p>'The LORD himself will fight for you; you need only be still' — this is the theological crystallization of the holy-war tradition in the Hebrew Bible. In the ANE, battles were commonly fought under the patronage of a divine warrior; but in Israelite holy war, YHWH is not a patron who empowers human soldiers but the primary combatant whose warriors must stand down to let him fight. The same principle governs Gideon's reduction of his army (Judges 7) and Jehoshaphat's battle without a sword (2 Chr 20:15-17). The NT re-applies this logic in Rom 12:19 ('vengeance is mine, says the LORD') and Rev 19:11-16 (Christ as the divine warrior).</p>",
        "15": "<p>'Why are you crying out to me? Tell the Israelites to move forward' — YHWH's rebuke of Moses's prayer implies that Moses was interceding when the proper response was action. This verse establishes a biblical principle that has come to be called the distinction between prayer and trust: sometimes crying out is itself a failure of trust, a substitute for faithful movement. The Mishnah records a discussion about whether the sea miraculously opened only when Israel's feet touched the water (based on this and Ps 114:3) — a tradition that emphasizes faith as the trigger of divine action.</p>",
        "16": "<p>Moses's staff (<em>maṭṭeh</em>) — the same staff with which he struck the Nile, turned it to blood, called plagues, and drew water from the rock — functions throughout Exodus as the instrument of divine power extended through human agency. The staff was not magical in itself; it was the sign of Moses's prophetic authority under YHWH. This literary coherence (same staff, same pattern of action) ties the Red Sea miracle to the plagues as part of one continuous series of YHWH's signs (<em>ʾôtôt</em>) against Egypt.</p>",
        "17": "<p>'I — I will harden the hearts of the Egyptians so that they will follow them' — the emphatic first-person pronoun (Hebrew <em>wa-ăni</em>) stresses YHWH's direct agency. The Egyptians' pursuit into the sea is not merely their own foolishness; it is the means by which YHWH 'will gain glory over Pharaoh and all his army, his chariots and his horsemen.' The audience of the revelation is named explicitly: the Egyptians will know YHWH. The knowledge-of-YHWH formula, which runs through the plague narratives, reaches its climax in the sea crossing.</p>",
        "18": "<p>'The Egyptians will know that I am YHWH' — the knowledge formula (<em>yāḏaʿ kî ʾănî YHWH</em>) occurs over seventy times in the book of Ezekiel and is the climactic theological claim of the exodus narrative. Egypt's imperial ideology claimed that Pharaoh was the son of Ra, the embodiment of divine order; the exodus demonstrated that YHWH, not Pharaoh's gods, controlled the forces of nature and history. The nations surrounding Israel were the wider audience: Rahab's confession in Josh 2:10-11 shows the Red Sea crossing had become known throughout Canaan and was producing the expected theological effect.</p>",
        "19": "<p>'The angel of God (<em>malʾak hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) who had been going before the Israelite army moved and went behind them' — the angel and the pillar are identified: 'the pillar of cloud moved from before them and stood behind them.' The angel of YHWH in Exodus functions as the divine presence that goes ahead of, protects, and guides Israel. This figure — at times indistinguishable from YHWH himself (Exod 3:2-6; 14:19) — becomes a key element in the Jewish concept of the divine mediating agent, and many patristic writers identified this angel as the pre-incarnate Son.</p>",
        "20": "<p>'Bringing darkness to the one and light to the other' — the same divine presence that illuminated Israel's way created blinding darkness for the Egyptians. This is the theological reversal of the ninth plague of darkness (Exod 10:21-23), where darkness covered Egypt while Israel had light in their dwellings. The spatial separation maintained by the pillar prevented the Egyptian forces from approaching during the night, creating the window of time for Israel to cross.</p>",
        "21": "<p>The mechanism of the sea-crossing involves a 'strong east wind' (<em>rûaḥ qādîm ʿazzāh</em>) driving the sea back all night, making 'dry ground.' The event engages natural means (wind, topography of the shallow sea) while attributing the result entirely to YHWH. The Sea of Reeds (<em>yam-sûp</em>) may refer to the area of the Bitter Lakes or the Gulf of Suez/Aqaba — various theories locate the crossing in different parts of the isthmus. The narrative's theological concern outweighs its geographical precision: what matters is that the impossible became possible through YHWH's direct action.</p>",
        "22": "<p>'The Israelites walked through the sea on dry ground, with walls of water on their right hand and on their left' — the repetition of this detail (also in v.29) marks it as theologically significant. The term 'dry ground' (<em>ḥārābāh</em>) echoes Genesis 1:9-10 where YHWH gathered the waters and the dry land appeared. The crossing is a new creation event — chaotic waters divided, dry ground for human passage, a new beginning for a redeemed people. Paul draws the baptismal implication explicitly: the crossing through the sea was corporate baptism 'into Moses' (1 Cor 10:1-2).</p>",
        "23": "<p>The Egyptians' pursuit into the sea — 'all Pharaoh's horses, chariots, and horsemen' — represents the pinnacle of military overconfidence. They followed the Israelites into the divided sea using the same route that had just opened supernaturally. The narrative does not explain their psychology; their entry into the sea is simply the consequence of pursuing a retreating enemy. The ancient reader would have recognized this as the fatal error of the overconfident army: following the pursued into favorable enemy terrain without recognizing the danger.</p>",
        "24": "<p>'In the morning watch, the LORD looked down on the Egyptian army through the pillar of fire and cloud' — the 'morning watch' (<em>ʾašmōret habbōqer</em>) was the last watch of the night (3 a.m. to dawn). YHWH's 'looking down' (<em>wayyaṣṣēp</em>) in a battle context is the language of divine combat — he reviews the enemy formation from his vantage point. Ancient Egyptian battle theology spoke of the pharaoh as a divine warrior who surveyed the battlefield from a divine vantage; here YHWH performs that survey from the pillar, the vehicle of his presence.</p>",
        "25": "<p>'He jammed the wheels of their chariots so that they drove with difficulty' — the mechanical failure of the chariot wheels in the soft, wet sea bed halted the pursuit. The Egyptians' recognition — 'Let us flee from before Israel, for YHWH fights for them against Egypt' — is the most remarkable theological statement in the chapter: Egypt's army acknowledges, at the moment of their destruction, exactly what Moses had declared to Israel in v.14. Their confession comes too late; the water has already been commanded to return.</p>",
        "26": "<p>Moses stretches his hand over the sea a second time (mirroring v.16) to return the waters. The symmetry of the two gestures — hand extended to divide, hand extended to restore — frames the entire crossing narrative as a single enclosed divine act. The staff/hand motif throughout Exodus connects the plagues, the sea-crossing, and the water-from-the-rock (Exod 17:5-6) as a coherent series of signs performed through Moses as YHWH's authorized agent.</p>",
        "27": "<p>'Moses stretched out his hand over the sea, and at daybreak the sea returned to its normal course' — <em>lĕʾêtānô</em>, 'to its normal course/strength': the waters return to their natural state, the miracle ends, and the Egyptian army is caught in the sea's return. The timing — at daybreak after a night of crossing — maximizes both the miracle (night crossing under divine light) and the judgment (dawn reveals the destruction of the entire army). The Song of the Sea (15:1-18) celebrates exactly this timing: 'You blew with your wind; the sea covered them.'</p>",
        "28": "<p>'The waters returned and covered the chariots and the horsemen; of all the host of Pharaoh that had followed them into the sea, not one of them remained' — the total annihilation (<em>lōʾ-nišʾar bāhem ʿad-ʾeḥād</em>, 'not one of them remained') is the narrative's most emphatic claim. No prisoner was taken, no soldier escaped. This total destruction is historically unparalleled in any Egyptian record (Egyptian official records never documented defeats), which is part of why no Egyptian account of the event survives. The annihilation of Pharaoh's army is the culminating sign that secures Israel's freedom permanently.</p>",
        "29": "<p>'But the Israelites had walked through the sea on dry ground' — the third occurrence of the 'dry ground' phrase (vv.21, 22, 29) creates a structural inclusio around the crossing narrative. The deliberate repetition hammers the theological contrast: the same sea that destroyed the Egyptians provided safe passage for Israel. The water is both judgment and salvation, differentiated entirely by YHWH's design. This dual function of water reappears in Noah's flood (same water that kills saves Noah's family), and Paul sees Christian baptism as participating in the same structure (1 Pet 3:20-21).</p>",
        "30": "<p>'That day YHWH saved Israel from the hand of the Egyptians' — the summary verse uses the verb <em>yāšaʿ</em> (to save), the root of the names Joshua and Jesus. The formula 'that day' (<em>hayyôm hahûʾ</em>) is the OT's technical phrase for the decisive day of YHWH's intervention — used for Passover, the Red Sea, and repeatedly for the anticipated Day of YHWH in the prophets (Joel 2:1; Amos 5:18; Isa 2:12). 'Israel saw the Egyptians dead on the seashore' — the evidence of YHWH's salvation was visible to all, requiring no faith to see but producing faith in response.</p>",
        "31": "<p>'Israel saw the great power that the LORD had displayed against the Egyptians, and the people feared YHWH and believed in YHWH and in his servant Moses' — the sequence is significant: seeing led to fear (proper response to theophany) which led to belief. The verb <em>wayyaʾmîn</em> (believed) is the Hiphil of <em>ʾāman</em> — 'to confirm, to consider reliable/trustworthy' — the root from which <em>ʾāmēn</em> derives. This moment of communal faith at the sea is paradoxically both a high point and a tragic contrast with the golden calf apostasy only weeks later (ch.32). The NT sees the wilderness generation as a warning about temporary faith that does not endure (Heb 3:7-19; 1 Cor 10:1-12).</p>"
    },
    "15": {
        "1": "<p>The Song of the Sea (<em>Šîrat hayyām</em>) is widely recognized as one of the oldest pieces of poetry in the Hebrew Bible. Linguistic analysis identifies archaic features: the pronominal suffix <em>-môw</em> instead of the later <em>-hemmāh</em>, archaic verbal forms, and metrical patterns that differ from later Hebrew poetry. Many scholars date its composition to the eleventh or twelfth century BCE or even earlier. It follows the literary form of the ANE victory hymn, celebrating YHWH as the triumphant divine warrior in the style of Canaanite battle poetry (especially the Baal cycle of Ugarit), but substituting YHWH for Baal as the cosmic victor.</p>",
        "2": "<p>'The LORD is my strength and my song; he has become my salvation' — this verse was recognized in ancient Israel as a foundational hymn fragment and was quoted verbatim in two later texts: Ps 118:14 (the great Hallel psalm sung at Passover) and Isa 12:2 (the song of the redeemed after YHWH's eschatological salvation). The deliberate re-use of the Song of the Sea's opening in these contexts shows how Israel understood later salvations as replaying the exodus pattern. The phrase <em>zimmirāt YHWH</em> (my strength and song/power) is a single construct noun: YHWH is both the source of strength and the subject of the song.</p>",
        "3": "<p>'The LORD is a warrior (<em>ʾîš milḥāmāh</em>); the LORD is his name' — this is the divine-warrior declaration at the heart of the song. ANE literature abounds with divine-warrior epithets: Baal as the storm-warrior who defeats Yam (Sea) and Mot (Death), Marduk as the warrior who slays Tiamat in Enuma Elish. Israel appropriates this widespread ANE mythological register but redirects it: the warrior who defeats the cosmic sea is YHWH, not the Baal cycle's protagonist. This demythologizes the combat while retaining its power — the victory at the Sea of Reeds is real history, not cosmic myth, but it carries the same theological weight.</p>",
        "4": "<p>'Pharaoh's chariots and his army he cast into the sea; his finest officers are drowned in the Sea of Reeds' — the verb <em>yārāh</em> (cast/throw) may be a wordplay on the same root that underlies <em>tôrāh</em> (teaching/instruction, from the causative 'to point/direct/throw'). The poem celebrates YHWH's 'throwing' Pharaoh's military into the sea just as a warrior throws a weapon. The 'finest officers' (<em>mibḥar šālîšāyw</em>) are the elite chariot officers — the cream of the Egyptian military establishment. Their drowning is a complete reversal of military hierarchy: the most powerful soldiers on earth meet total defeat.</p>",
        "5": "<p>'The great deep (<em>tehōmōt</em>) covered them' — <em>tehōm</em> is the deep-water abyss of Genesis 1:2 that YHWH separated at creation ('the darkness over the face of the deep'). The Song of the Sea deliberately invokes creation language: the same primordial waters that YHWH separated to make the world suitable for life are now the instrument of judgment against those who oppose YHWH's redemptive purpose. The enemy 'went down to the depths like a stone' — precise, vivid, final. This de-creation imagery for judgment appears throughout the prophets and in Revelation's image of the sea giving up its dead (Rev 20:13).</p>",
        "6": "<p>'Your right hand, O LORD, is majestic in power; your right hand, O LORD, shattered the enemy' — the 'right hand' (<em>yĕmînĕkā</em>) is the place of power and honor in ancient Near Eastern culture; the king placed his trusted officials at his right hand, and military power was concentrated in the right arm. The repetition ('your right hand...your right hand') is a feature of archaic Hebrew poetry's parallelism and possibly indicates a responsorial tradition — different groups singing alternate lines. The theological claim is that YHWH's power is not merely greater than Egypt's but categorically different in kind.</p>",
        "7": "<p>'In the greatness of your majesty (<em>gaʾōnĕkā</em>) you overthrew your adversaries' — <em>gaʾôn</em> (majesty, pride, excellence) is used in Hebrew both positively for divine majesty (Ps 93:1) and negatively for human arrogance (Isa 13:11). The same quality is divine virtue when applied to YHWH and mortal sin when applied to humans — the difference being that YHWH's greatness is the source and standard from which human greatness should derive but doesn't. The fire metaphor ('you unleashed your burning wrath') anticipates the fire of Sinai and the prophetic tradition of YHWH's wrath as fire (Nah 1:6; Jer 4:4).</p>",
        "8": "<p>'By the blast of your nostrils (<em>bĕrûaḥ ʾappekā</em>) the waters piled up' — the same divine breath (<em>rûaḥ</em>, wind/breath/spirit) that created the world (Gen 1:2), parted the sea (Exod 14:21), and will be given at Pentecost (Acts 2) is here personified as YHWH's nostril-blast in battle. The image is visceral and anthropomorphic, drawing on ancient combat imagery where the warrior's snorting breath drives his enemies before him. The 'flowing waters stood upright like a wall' is poetic recollection of the prose description in 14:22 — the poem and prose narratives are two perspectives on the same event.</p>",
        "9": "<p>'The enemy said, “I will pursue, I will overtake, I will divide the plunder”' — the enemy's boastful interior monologue is one of the most effective rhetorical devices in ancient Hebrew poetry. The sevenfold 'I will' (five explicit verbs plus two implied) mimics the structure of divine declaration but issues from a mortal who has no power to guarantee his own words. The contrast with what actually happened — complete drowning — is devastating. The enemy's self-confident calculation ('my hand shall destroy them') is the prototype of every human pretension to control outcomes that belong to YHWH alone (cf. Isa 10:8-11; Luke 12:17-20).</p>",
        "10": "<p>'But you blew with your wind (<em>nāšaptā bĕrûḥăkā</em>); the sea covered them' — the abrupt reversal from the enemy's boasting in v.9 to the divine action in v.10 is compressed into a single breath. The 'you' is emphatic in Hebrew, thrown against the 'my' of the enemy's speech. 'They sank like lead in the mighty waters' — the image is of permanent, irrecoverable submersion. Lead (<em>ʿōpāret</em>) sinks without trace; the Egyptian army has disappeared. The language of sinking 'like lead' appears in a slightly different form in Neh 9:11, showing the Song's continued influence on Israel's liturgical memory.</p>",
        "11": "<p>'Who is like you, O LORD, among the gods?' — this is not monotheism in the later philosophical sense but an incomparability declaration, a common genre in ANE praise literature. The gods (<em>ʾēlîm</em>) are not denied existence here; the claim is that none can compare to YHWH in power, holiness, or awesome deeds. This incomparability declaration is the primary form of Israel's early monotheism: not 'there are no other gods' but 'no other god is in YHWH's category.' The same declaration appears in Ps 89:6-8; 86:8; Jer 10:6. By the postexilic period, the incomparability declaration had fully absorbed the denial of other gods' reality (Isa 44:6-8; 45:5-7).</p>",
        "12": "<p>'You stretched out your right hand; the earth swallowed them' — a shift in imagery from drowning (water) to swallowing (earth/Sheol). The Hebrew <em>tiblaʿēmô ʾāreṣ</em> (the earth swallowed them) uses the same verb as Korah's rebellion where the ground opened and swallowed the rebels (Num 16:32). The movement from sea to earth in the Song may reflect the ANE cosmic geography where the underworld lay beneath both sea and earth — enemies swallowed by the sea go to the realm of death. YHWH's power extends throughout the vertical cosmos: sky (pillar of cloud), sea (walls of water), and earth (swallowing) are all his instruments.</p>",
        "13": "<p>'In your steadfast love (<em>ḥeseḏ</em>) you have led the people you redeemed' — the Song pivots from past act (the sea crossing) to future destination (the land). <em>Ḥeseḏ</em> here is YHWH's covenant loyalty — the quality that makes his redemption reliable and his leadership dependable. The 'holy abode' (<em>nĕwēh qoḏšĕkā</em>) refers to the promised land in its entirety, not yet to Jerusalem or the temple (which are anticipated in v.17). The song is sung before Israel has entered Canaan — it celebrates a future that is so certain because YHWH's covenant love guarantees it that it can be sung in the past tense as already accomplished.</p>",
        "14": "<p>'The peoples heard and trembled; anguish seized the inhabitants of Philistia' — the song anticipates the geopolitical effect of the exodus. The 'nations' who tremble include Philistia, Edom, and Moab — precisely the peoples Israel will encounter on the way to and at the edge of Canaan. The fulfillment of this prediction is confirmed by Rahab in Jericho: 'We have heard how the LORD dried up the water of the Red Sea before you when you came out of Egypt... as soon as we heard it, our hearts melted, and there was no spirit left in any man because of you' (Josh 2:10-11). The Song anticipates what the Joshua narrative confirms.</p>",
        "15": "<p>'Then the chiefs of Edom were terrified; the leaders of Moab were seized with trembling' — Edom and Moab were Israel's closest ethnic relatives (Edom descended from Esau, Moab from Lot) but would become persistent opponents. Their terror at YHWH's acts is documented in Numbers' accounts of Israel's later encounters with them (Num 20-25). 'The inhabitants of Canaan have melted away' — the same language Rahab uses in Josh 2:9 (<em>nāmōg</em>, melted away). The Song of the Sea was prophetically accurate: its prediction of the nations' terror at YHWH's acts was fulfilled in the Canaanite period.</p>",
        "16": "<p>'Terror and dread fall on them; by the power of your arm they are still as stone, until your people pass by, O LORD' — the language of <em>ʾêmātāh wāfaḥad</em> (terror and dread) is an idiom for the fear that YHWH's presence produces in his enemies, related to the concept of the divine warrior's battle-shout that paralyzes opponents. The image 'still as stone' suggests complete paralysis — the nations are immobilized while YHWH's people pass through their territory. The theology of divine protection-in-transit becomes a theme in the prophetic tradition: YHWH will clear the way for his people's return from exile (Isa 40:3-4; 52:12).</p>",
        "17": "<p>'You will bring them in and plant them (<em>tiṭṭāʿēmô</em>) on your own mountain — the place, O LORD, you made for your own dwelling' — the 'mountain of YHWH's inheritance' is Zion/Jerusalem, not yet conquered or even named. The Song anticipates the entire trajectory of Israelite history from the sea to the temple: exodus → wilderness → conquest → monarchy → temple. The planting metaphor (<em>tiṭṭāʿēmô</em>) appears also in Ps 80:8-9 (Israel as a vine transplanted from Egypt) and Isa 5:1-7 (the vineyard parable). The sanctuary 'your hands established' points forward to the Solomonic temple, which is described as built by YHWH's own design (1 Chr 28:19).</p>",
        "18": "<p>'The LORD will reign forever and ever' — the Song concludes with a declaration of YHWH's eternal kingship that is the theological climax of the entire exodus narrative. This kingship declaration forms the backbone of Israel's liturgical tradition: Ps 93:1; 96:10; 97:1; 99:1 all begin 'The LORD reigns' and are likely connected to ancient enthronement festivals. The kingdom of YHWH is the meta-narrative of the OT that the NT announces as having arrived in Jesus: 'The kingdom of God is at hand' (Mark 1:15) and 'The kingdom of the world has become the kingdom of our Lord and of his Christ, and he shall reign forever and ever' (Rev 11:15) both draw directly on Exod 15:18.</p>",
        "19": "<p>The prose recapitulation (v.19) summarizes the crossing before the scene transitions to Miriam's antiphon. This alternation of poetry and prose at key narrative moments (also at the crossing of the Jordan in Josh 3-5, with Ps 114 as the poetry) is a feature of biblical historiography: the prose provides the narrative; the poetry provides the theological interpretation. The repetition serves a liturgical purpose: the song was composed to be sung, and the prose surroundings kept it embedded in the historical event rather than floating free as purely cultic poetry.</p>",
        "20": "<p>Miriam is the first person in the Bible called a <em>nĕbîʾāh</em> (prophetess); later prophetesses include Deborah (Judg 4:4), Huldah (2 Kgs 22:14), and Noadiah (Neh 6:14). She is identified as Aaron's sister (and by extension Moses's sister, matching the figure in ch.2), establishing a family leadership triad — Moses, Aaron, and Miriam — that recurs in Numbers (Num 12; 20). The women's tambourine-and-dance celebration of military victory was an established Israelite custom: Jephthah's daughter greets him with tambourines (Judg 11:34), and the women sing over David's victory with tambourines and dancing (1 Sam 18:6-7). This was the traditional role of women in victory celebration.</p>",
        "21": "<p>Miriam's response — 'Sing to the LORD, for he has triumphed gloriously; horse and rider he has thrown into the sea' — is identical to Moses's opening verse (15:1b). This antiphonal structure (leader sings, congregation responds) reflects ancient Israelite worship: the people repeat or respond to the cantor's lead. Some scholars argue that Miriam's verse is the <em>original</em> Song of the Sea, with Moses's longer version (15:1-18) being the literary expansion. Either way, the antiphonal structure points to communal, participatory worship rather than solo performance — the entire people, men with Moses and women with Miriam, sing together.</p>",
        "22": "<p>The transition from the Song of the Sea (15:1-21) to the wilderness journey (15:22ff.) is abrupt and deliberately so: the celebration ends and the testing begins immediately. 'Moses led Israel away from the Sea of Reeds, and they went into the wilderness of Shur' — Shur is the wilderness east of Egypt, stretching from the Nile delta toward the Sinai Peninsula. 'Three days in the wilderness and found no water' establishes the pattern of the wilderness testing: the people are placed under pressure (thirst, hunger, enemies) to reveal what is in their hearts (Deut 8:2-3). The three-day motif recurs throughout the OT as the testing period before divine provision.</p>",
        "23": "<p>Marah (<em>mārāh</em>, 'bitter') gave its name to a place of bitter water — a likely site near modern ʿAyn Hawarah in the Sinai, where the water is brackish. The bitterness of the water becomes a symbol for the bitterness of Israel's situation and its complaint. The Hebrew root <em>mārāh</em> (bitter, to be bitter) is also the root of 'Naomi' (pleasantness) → 'Mara' (bitter) in Ruth 1:20: 'Do not call me Naomi; call me Mara, for the Almighty has dealt very bitterly with me.' The Marah episode introduces the bitterness motif that will recur throughout the wilderness narrative as Israel's alternating experience of divine provision and complaint.</p>",
        "24": "<p>'The people grumbled (<em>wayyillônû</em>) against Moses' — this is the first use of <em>lûn</em> (to murmur, grumble) in the exodus narrative; the verb will become virtually the signature word of the wilderness generation (Exod 16:2, 7, 8; Num 14:2, 27, 36; 16:11). The grumbling is always framed as directed against Moses but evaluated by YHWH as directed against himself (16:8: 'your grumbling is not against us but against YHWH'). The murmuring motif is what defines the wilderness generation negatively in both the OT summaries (Ps 106:25; Neh 9:17) and the NT's use of it as a warning (1 Cor 10:10; Phil 2:14).</p>",
        "25": "<p>YHWH 'showed him a piece of wood' (<em>ʿēṣ</em>); Moses threw it into the water and it became sweet. The mechanism is not explained — the focus is on divine instruction, human obedience, and divine result. YHWH then 'tested him there' — the same verb (<em>nāsāh</em>) used for testing/proving; the wilderness is explicitly a site of divine testing (Deut 8:2). The wood-sweetening-bitter-waters image generated a rich tradition of interpretation: the rabbis connected it to the Torah as the 'tree of life' (Prov 3:18) that sweetens the bitterness of life; Christian interpreters saw a proto-type of the cross transforming judgment into salvation.</p>",
        "26": "<p>'If you will carefully listen to the voice of the LORD your God' — the conditional covenant structure appears for the first time in the narrative: obedience leads to health and blessing; disobedience leads to the diseases of Egypt. 'I am YHWH your healer (<em>YHWH rophekā</em>)' is one of the compound divine names revealing aspects of YHWH's character — here: YHWH as physician. The other compound names appear throughout Exodus and the wilderness narratives: YHWH-Nissi (17:15), YHWH-Mĕqaddĕškem (31:13). The promise 'none of the diseases of Egypt' ties obedience to the liberation narrative: Egypt's diseases are what YHWH used against Pharaoh; covenant obedience puts Israel on the other side of that judgment.</p>",
        "27": "<p>Elim — 'twelve springs and seventy palm trees' — provides abundant, sweet water after Marah's bitter water. The numbers are likely symbolic as well as literal: twelve corresponds to the twelve tribes of Israel; seventy corresponds to the seventy elders (Exod 24:1; Num 11:16) and the seventy nations of Genesis 10. Elim is the provision that follows testing — the pattern of wilderness theology in miniature. It foreshadows the abundance YHWH intends for his people but which requires the testing period to develop the trust and obedience that can receive it rightly. Elim is probably identified with modern Wadi Gharandel, a well-watered oasis on the western Sinai coast.</p>"
    }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'exodus')
    merge_comm(existing, EXODUS_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'exodus', existing)
    for ch in ['13', '14', '15']:
        vv = existing.get(ch, {})
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(vv)} verse(s) with context commentary')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
